        "body": "# Bug Report\r\n\r\n### 🔎 Search Terms\r\n\r\n- uninitialized variable\r\n- unassigned variable\r\n- unassigned declaration\r\n\r\n### 🕗 Version & Regression Information\r\n\r\n- 5.0.2\r\n\r\n### ⏯ Playground Link\r\n\r\n[Playground link with relevant code](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#code/GYVwdgxgLglg9mABMAhjANgHgCoD4AUEK66ARihANYBci+AbsSAKa3YCUiAvLovXDAAmnAN4AoRJMTpmUaSgDOUAGpNWibAG4JUgE6yQupPk49EREuSr50ilWvZiAvkA)\r\n\r\n### 💻 Code\r\n\r\n```ts\r\nfunction fail<T>(callback: (value: T) => void) {\r\n    let lastValue: T;\r\n    return () => callback(lastValue)\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### 🙁 Actual behavior\r\n\r\nIn the provided code snippet, the function `fail` takes a callback function with a generic type parameter `T`. The variable `lastValue` of type `T` is not initialized, which means it defaults to `undefined`. Consequently, when the `callback` function is called with `lastValue` as its argument, it always receives `undefined` even though it expects a value of type `T`.\r\n\r\n### 🙂 Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThere should either be an error at compile-time.\r\n",
